      <h2>How Does It Hydrate Itself?</h2>
      <p>
        Unlike many birds, the Malabar Pied Hornbill doesn't drink water in the
        traditional sense. Its massive beak makes it awkward and difficult to
        sip from ponds or streams. Instead, it survives by consuming juicy,
        water-rich fruits like figs, berries, and other seasonal forest produce.
        These fruits provide both nutrition and hydration, sustaining the bird
        even in dry environments.
      </p>
      <p>
        Interestingly, not all hornbills follow this rule. In Africa, some
        hornbill species—like the Southern Yellow-billed Hornbill—are observed
        drinking water directly from sources when available. This shows that
        while hydration strategies vary, the Malabar Pied Hornbill has evolved
        to rely almost entirely on its fruit diet.
      </p>
