      <h2>General Behavior</h2>
      <p>
        Hornbills are highly social birds. The Malabar Pied Hornbill often moves
        in packs, filling the forest with their loud calls and heavy wingbeats.
        They are usually seen flying in small groups, and pairs are particularly
        inseparable—often staying side by side whether perching or flying.
      </p>
      <p>
        They are also highly territorial. Their loud, croaking calls echo
        through the forest canopy, serving both as communication within the
        flock and as a way to mark their presence.
      </p>

      <h2>A Remarkable Family Ritual</h2>
      <p>
        Perhaps the most extraordinary behavior of the Malabar Pied Hornbill is
        seen during breeding season. The female selects a hollow tree cavity and
        seals herself inside with a wall of mud, droppings, and fruit pulp,
        leaving only a small slit open. She remains trapped in this dark chamber
        for weeks, depending entirely on the male to deliver food through the
        slit.
      </p>
      <p>
        Inside, she lays eggs and tends to her chicks. During this period, she
        molts most of her feathers, making flight impossible. Once the chicks
        grow large enough and their feathers are developed, the female breaks
        out of her prison. From that point, both parents share the
        responsibility of feeding their young until they are ready to leave the
        nest.
      </p>
      <p>
        This incredible strategy protects the vulnerable female and chicks from
        predators and harsh weather, though it places enormous pressure on the
        male to provide consistently.
      </p>
